{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}} {{infobox person | image = Brian O'Shaughnessy.png | image_size = | alt = | caption = | name = Brian Joseph O'Shaughnessy | birth_date = 10 September 1925 | birth_place = [[Kew, Victoria]], [[Australia]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2010|07|07|1925|09|10}} | death_place = | occupation = Philosopher, writer}} '''Brian Joseph O'Shaughnessy''' (10 September 1925 – 7 July 2010)<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/14/brian-oshaughnessy-obituary Obituary], guardian.co.uk; 14 July 2010; accessed 16 May 2014.</ref> was an Australian [[philosophy of mind|philosopher of mind]], who lived in [[London]] and taught at [[King's College London]]. He published influential papers on the nature of physical action and the will, at a time when this was quite unfashionable.<ref name="theguardian.com">https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/14/brian-oshaughnessy-obituary</ref>
==Biography== He was born in Kew, a suburb of [[Melbourne]] in [[Australia]], where his father was a doctor.<ref name="theguardian.com"/> He studied at Xavier College and then attended [[Melbourne University]], firstly studying engineering before changing to philosophy. He graduated in 1950 and then went to [[England]] to continue his studies at [[Oxford University]].<ref name="Bio2008-10-24">{{cite web|date=24 October 2008|title=Brian O'Shaughnessy|work=King's College London|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/schools/humanities/depts/philosophy/people/emeritus/oshaughnessy.html|accessdate=23 February 2010}}</ref> He is buried in [[Highgate Cemetery]] in north [[London]] in the first section on the left immediately upon entering the Eastern Cemetery.
