[[File:Horace Jayne 1899.jpg|thumb|Dr. Jayne in 1899.]] '''Horace Fort Jayne''' (5 March 1859, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania – 9 July 1913, Wallingford, Pennsylvania)<ref name=ea>{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Jayne, Horace}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[zoology|zoölogist]] and educator.
==Biography== He was the son of [[patent medicine]] millionaire Dr. David Jayne (1799-1866) and Hannah Fort Jayne (1827&ndash;1904).<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/136435107 Hannah Fort Jayne], from Find-A-Grave.</ref>
He was educated at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]], 1879; [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]], 1882), and studied [[biology]] at the universities of [[University of Leipzig|Leipzig]] and [[Friedrich Schiller University of Jena|Jena]] in 1882–1883, and at [[Johns Hopkins University|Johns Hopkins]] for a year. In 1884 he was appointed [[professor]] of vertebrate morphology at [[Wistar Institute|The Wistar Institute of Anatomy and Biology]], and became a director of the institute. He was a professor of zoölogy at the University of Pennsylvania from 1894 to 1905, secretary of Penn's biological faculty (1884–1889), and [[dean (education)|dean]] of Penn's college faculty (1889–1894). He became a trustee of [[Drexel University|Drexel Institute]], and served as co-editor of several scientific journals.<ref>{{NIE}}</ref>
He married ethnologist [[Caroline Furness Jayne]] (1873&ndash;1909), and they had two children. Their son, [[Horace H. F. Jayne]] (1898&ndash;1975), became the first curator of Chinese art at the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], and later was director of the [[University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]], and vice director of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].
==Works== *''Abnormalities Observed in the North American Coleoptera'' (1880) *''Revision of the Dermestidœ of North America'' (1882) *''Mammalian Anatomy'' (1898) He was also the author of many scientific papers.<ref name=ea/>
