'''Kriyā''' (in [[Sanskrit]] "action, deed, effort") most commonly refers to a "completed action", technique or practice within a [[yoga]] discipline meant to achieve a specific result. Another meaning of Kriya is an outward physical manifestation of awakened [[Kundalini energy|kundalini]], such as a spontaneous body movement related to Kundalini energy flow.

==Etymology==
''Kriyā'' is a [[Sanskrit]] term, derived from the Sanskrit root, ''kri'', meaning "to do". ''Kriyā'' means "action, deed, effort". The word [[karma]] is also derived from the Sanskrit root ''{{IAST|√kṛ}}'' (kri) {{lang|sa|कृ}}, meaning "to do, make, perform, accomplish, cause, effect, prepare, undertake".<ref name=mmw>see:
* [http://www.ibiblio.org/sripedia/ebooks/mw/0300/mw__0334.html kṛ, कृ] Monier Monier-Williams, [http://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/monier/ Monier Williams Sanskrit-English Dictionary (2008 revision)], pp 300-301;
* Carl Cappeller (1999), Monier-Williams: A Sanskrit-English Dictionary, Etymological and Philologically Arranged with Special Reference to Cognate Indo-European Languages, Asian Educational Services, {{ISBN|978-8120603691}}</ref><ref>Mulla & Krishnan (2009), Do Karma-Yogis Make Better Leaders? Exploring the Relationship between the Leader's Karma-Yoga and Transformational Leadership, Journal of Human Values, 15(2), pp 167-183</ref> Karma is related to verbal proto-Indo-European root *kwer- "to make, form".<ref>John Algeo and Thomas Pyles (2010), The Origins and Development of the English Language, 6th Edition, {{ISBN|978-1428231450}}, pp 54-55</ref>

The root ''kṛ'' (kri) is very common in ancient Sanskrit literature, and it is relied upon to explain ideas in [[Rigveda]], other Vedas, Upanishads, Puranas, the Epics of Hinduism.<ref name=mmw/><ref>See Rigveda 9.69.5, 10.159.4, 10.95.2, Svetâsvatara Upanishad 2.7.v.1, Mahabharata 1.5141, etc.</ref> The root "kri" also appears in the word Sans'''kri'''t, to imply a language that is "well made".

==Origins==
===Bhagavad Gita===
[[File:Krishna instructing Arjuna.jpg|thumb|[[Krishna]] instructing Arjuna]]

The Bhagavad Gita does not teach kriya yoga by name. Yogananda and his teachers have claimed that the practice itself is described in the ''[[Bhagavad Gita]]''.<ref>Paramahansa Yogananda, ''Autobiography of a Yogi''</ref> According to [[Paramahansa Yogananda]] in his book ''[[Bhagavad Gita (Yogananda)|God Talks with Arjuna: The Bhagavad Gita]]'', [[Krishna]] describes kriya yoga as:
{{quote|Offering inhaling breath into the outgoing breath, and offering the outgoing breath into the inhaling breath, the yogi neutralizes both these breaths; he thus releases the life force from the heart and brings it under his control.<ref>[[Paramahansa Yogananda]] (1995). ''God Talks with Arjuna: The Bhagavad Gita'' (Verse IV:29), First Edition. Self-Realization Fellowship. {{ISBN|0-87612-030-3}}.</ref>}}

The Bihar School, which also teaches similar techniques of kriya yoga, claims that the descriptions of kriya yoga in the Yoga Sūtras and the Bhagavad Gīta are not related. <ref>Swami Satyananda, ''Asana, Pranayama, Mudra, Bandha''</ref>

===Yoga Sutras of Patanjali===
[[File:patanjali.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Patanjali|Patañjali]] statue (traditional form indicating [[Kundalini energy|Kundalini]] or incarnation of [[Shesha]])]]

The ''[[Yoga Sutras of Patanjali]]'' are generally viewed as a compendium of multiple traditions of yoga.{{sfn|Feuerstein|1978|p=108}}{{sfn|Tola|Dragonetti|Prithipaul|1987|p=x}}{{sfn|Wuyastik|2011|p=33}} According to Feuerstein, the ''Yoga Sutras'' are a condensation of two different traditions, namely "eight limb yoga" (''ashtanga yoga'') and action yoga (''Kriyā yoga''),{{sfn|Feuerstein|1978|p=108}} the description of the eight limbs being an interpolation into the text on ''kriya''.{{sfn|Stiles|2011}}
According to George Feuerstein, ''kriya yoga'' is contained in chapter 1, chapter 2 verse 1-27, chapter 3 except verse 54, and chapter 4.{{sfn|Feuerstein|1978|p=108}} The "eight limb yoga" is described in chapter 2 verse 28-55, and chapter 3 verse 3 and 54.{{sfn|Feuerstein|1978|p=108}}

According to Miller, ''Kriya yoga'' is the "active performance of yoga".{{sfn|Miller|2009|p=44}} It is composed of part of the [[niyama]]s, "observances", the second limb of Patanjali's eight limbs.{{sfn|Miller|2009|p=44}} According to Miller, ''Kriya yoga'' is a threefold discipline, involving [[Tapas (Sanskrit)|ascetic practice]], the study and chanting of sacred hymns and syllables, and dedication to god.{{sfn|Miller|2009|p=44}}

Miller also notes that some commentators regard the first five limbs together as ''kriya yoga'', but that Patanjali himself states ''kriya yoga'' to be a subset of the second limb.{{sfn|Miller|2009|p=45}}

It is notable, that the kriya yogi is therefor not bound by the other yamas and niyamas and hence is not bound by the rules of cleanliness, non-violence, truthfulness, chastity and various other seemingly monastic practices. This makes the kriya yogi potentially similar

==Contemporary usage==
===Mahavatar Babaji===
The story of [[Lahiri Mahasaya]] receiving initiation into Kriya Yoga by the yogi [[Mahavatar Babaji]] in 1861 is recounted in ''Autobiography of a Yogi''.<ref>''Autobiography of a Yogi'', chapter 34, Materializing a Palace in the Himalayas, by Paramahansa Yogananda</ref> Yogananda wrote that at that meeting, Mahavatar Babaji told Lahiri Mahasaya, "The Kriya Yoga that I am giving to the world through you in this nineteenth century, is a revival of the same science that Krishna gave millenniums ago to Arjuna; and was later known to Patanjali, and to Christ, St. John, St. Paul, and other disciples".<ref name="Yogananda 1997 273, The Science of Kriya Yoga"/> Yogananda also wrote that Babaji and Christ were in continual communion and together, "have planned the spiritual technique of salvation for this age."<ref>{{cite book |last=Miller |first=Timothy |title=America's Alternative Religions |publisher=SUNY Press |year=1995 |page=178 |isbn =0791423972 }}</ref><ref>''Autobiography of a Yogi'', chapter 33, pg.307, by Paramahansa Yogananda</ref>

[[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]] first told Yogananda, confirmed later directly by Mahavatar Babaji, that he had been chosen to bring Kriya Yoga to the West.<ref>''Autobiography of a Yogi'', ch. 37.</ref>.  Yogananda then brought Kriya Yoga to the United States and Europe beginning in 1920 and continues to this day through his organization [[Self-Realization Fellowship]]. In India the fellowship is called [[Yogoda Satsanga Society of India]].<ref>''Autobiography of a Yogi'', ch. 26.</ref>

According to Yogananda,:
{{quote|[[Kriya Yoga]] is a simple, psychological method by which human blood is decarbonated and recharged with oxygen. The atoms of this extra oxygen are transmuted into life current to rejuvenate the brain and spinal centers. By stopping the accumulation of venous blood, the yogi is able to lessen or prevent the decay of tissues. The advanced yogi transmutes his cells into energy.<ref name="Yogananda 1997 273, The Science of Kriya Yoga">{{cite book |last=Yogananda |first=Paramahansa |title= Autobiography of a Yogi |year=1997 |publisher=Self-Realization Fellowship |isbn=0876120869|page=273, The Science of Kriya Yoga }}</ref>}}

=== Sudarshan Kriya ===
Sudarshan Kriya is a set of breathing techniques promoted since 1982 by Sri Sri Ravi Shankar.<ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-09-09/bangalore/27189063_1_sudarshan-kriya-sudarshan-kriya-spinal-cord</ref>

Sudharshan Kriya employs a variety of breathing patterns.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zope|first1=SameerA|last2=Zope|first2=RakeshA|title=Sudarshan kriya yoga: Breathing for health|journal=International Journal of Yoga|volume=6|issue=1|pages=4|doi=10.4103/0973-6131.105935}}</ref><ref>http://www.health.harvard.edu/newsletters/Harvard_Mental_Health_Letter/2009/April/Yoga-for-anxiety-and-depression</ref>

===Baba Haidakhan===
Publications on Babaji describe Kriya Yoga as practiced by Baba Haidakhan who died in 1984.<ref>{{cite book |first=Gaura |last=Devi |year=2001 |title=Fire of Transformation. My life with Babaji |location=Devon, UK |publisher=Nymet Press |isbn=0-9541839-0-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Giridhari Lal |last=Mishra |year=2011 |title=From Age to Age: Stories of Haidakhan Babaji |publisher=American Haidakhan Samaj |isbn=978-0578085463}}</ref> [[Haidakhan Babaji]], simply called "Babaji" or Bhole Baba by his students and devotees, was a teacher who appeared in northern [[India]] ([[Uttarakhand]]) and taught publicly from 1970 to 1984.

Some modern teachers and institutions consider the entire Yoga Sutras to be Kriya Yoga, although Patanjali only relates the term Kriya Yoga to these three foundation practices (tapas, swadhyaya, Ishwara pranidhana). Breathing practices with attention along the spine are often included, along with other physical practices. It is useful for the student of yoga to be aware of these different approaches, so as to not get confused by the various public offerings.<ref>http://www.swamij.com/yoga-sutras-20109.htm</ref>

